The number of recruits from Ukraine preparing to be sent to Donbas has been named
The official representative of the People's Police of the self-proclaimed Luhansk People's Republic (LPR), Andrei Marochko, said that in the winter of 2018-2019, Ukraine will send no less than 3,000 new recruits to Donbas.
According to him, in this way Kiev plans to "at least in some way complete the units".
"The unwillingness of Ukrainian citizens to serve in the ranks of the Armed Forces of Ukraine, mass dismissals have led to low staffing of the units", Marochko said, as quoted by RIA Novosti.
He also did not rule out that the real figures of Ukrainians conscripted into the army could be increased if necessary.
In 2014-2017, Kiev launched a so-called anti-terrorist operation (ATO), which was later replaced by a joint force operation (JF).
It was supposed that this measure would strengthen the role of Ukrainian security forces in resolving the situation.
At the end of August 2018, the situation in Donbas escalated because of the assassination of the head of the DPR, Alexander Zakharchenko.
The DNR authorities qualified what happened as a terrorist attack.
In the course of the criminal investigation, several people involved in the explosion were detained.
According to preliminary data, they confirmed that the sabotage was organized by the Ukrainian special services.
US authorities forced Musk to step down as Tesla chairman
American businessman Elon Musk will step down as chairman of the board of directors of the company he founded, Tesla, at the request of US authorities.
To settle claims from the Federal Securities and Exchange Commission, the entrepreneur will also pay $20 million
According to CNBC, the pre-trial arrangement with the agency allows Musk to remain in a senior position at Tesla.
At the same time, he must pay $20 million and step down as chairman of the board of directors within 45 days of the agreement and for at least three years.
Two independent directors will be appointed to take his place.
It is specified that the arrangement has yet to be approved by the court.
On September 28, it was revealed that the US Securities and Exchange Commission had accused Musk of misleading shareholders by claiming that there were sufficient funds to buy back the company's shares, and sued the entrepreneur.
It comes after the businessman posted on Twitter that he wanted to buy back Tesla shares at $420 apiece, but never did so.
After the tweet, the company's shares rose nearly 11%.
British Foreign Office chief compares EU to Soviet Union and prison
British Foreign Secretary Jeremy Hunt has compared the European Union to the Soviet Union and accused Brussels of taking member states prisoner.
The diplomat made this statement at the congress of the ruling Conservative Party in Birmingham, which opened on Sunday, September 30.
As the Daily Mail notes, Hunt has thus commented on the difficulties in the Brexit negotiation process.
Whatever happened to the belief in and ideals of the European dream?
The EU was created to protect freedom, and the Soviet Union did not let anyone leave it.
The lesson of history is clear: if you turn the EU from a community into a prison, the desire to leave it will not diminish, but will only grow, and we will not be the only prisoner who will want to escape from captivity, "declared the Minister.
He also added that attempts to punish Britain for the decision to leave the European Union will only exacerbate the crisis, Gazeta.ru notes.
In mid-September, British Prime Minister Theresa May said that the Brexit negotiations had reached an impasse.
This is how she commented on the outcome of the informal EU summit in Salzburg.
The Brexit decision was made in 2016 following a referendum.
The United Kingdom's exit is expected to take place before April 2019, but negotiations with Brussels on this issue are complicated by many factors.
In particular, there is still no clear agreement on how the parties will interact after London leaves the community.
In addition, the question of the Irish border remains open.
South Korea's president who received mushrooms from North Korea was given two dogs
South Korean President Moon Jae-in received two puppies as a gift from North Korean leader Kim Jong-un after a visit to Pyongyang.
This is reported by Reuters with reference to a representative of the South Korean president's administration.
"During the summit, a pair of dogs of Phunsan breed were offered as gifts.
On Thursday, they were received, "the agency reported.
The dogs are about a year old and were given several kilograms of food by the North Korean side "to help them adapt".
The gift was made in honor of the inter-Korean summit, which took place from 18 to 20 September in Pyongyang.
Hunting breed Phunsan from North Korean wolves and got its name from one of the districts of the DPRK.
As the agency notes, Moon loves animals, and already has two such dogs, which were given to him by former North Korean leader Kim Jong Il.
Dogs are not the only gift.
Kim Jong-un also handed his counterpart two tons of delicate matsutake mushrooms.
He ordered that the mushrooms be distributed to members of separated families during the Korean War who had not yet been reunited with their loved ones from the DPRK.
