In Indonesia, more than 100 inmates escape from prison after earthquake
More than 100 prisoners have escaped from a prison in Indonesia's Central Sulawesi province.
The escape was made possible after two powerful earthquakes on the island of magnitude 7.2 and 7.4.
According to The Jakarta Post, the incident occurred on September 28, when detainees at a prison in Palu demanded their release in connection with the tremors.
More than 340 inmates staged a riot and set fire to the facility.
Police who arrived at the scene partially brought the situation under control, but more than 100 people escaped from the prison.
The building itself has been severely damaged, and the guards are struggling to hold the prisoners.
The number of victims of the earthquake and tsunami that struck Sulawesi has risen to 832.
As a result, transportation, electricity and communications to some areas of the island are still not being established.
"Golden Pearl" for "ultimate realism"
For the third time in history, the San Sebastian International Film Festival has recognized a Spanish film as the best film of the year.
The main award - "The Golden Shell" - was awarded to the drama "Between the Two Seas", directed by Isaki Lacuesta.
This film, with almost documentary realism, tells the complicated story of the life of two brothers in the Spanish seaside province of Cadiz - Lacuesta presented a sequel to his 2006 film, The Legend of Time.
At the awards ceremony of the San Sebastian Film Festival, the creators of the Argentine thriller "Red" were honored, which was awarded in several categories.
Benjamin Naistatt was announced director of the year, Pedro Sotero was awarded for cinematography, and Dario Grandinetti was named best actor.
The actress of the year at the San Sebastian Film Festival was Pia Tjelta from Norway.
The jury praised her for her performance in Blind Spot, a drama about the life of one family after their daughter's suicide attempt.
The film was the directorial debut of Swedish actress Tuva Novotna.
In the category "best screenplay", the films "Julie" and "Faithful Man" shared the victory.
A special jury prize was awarded to the Philippine crime drama Alpha: The Right to Kill.
Dizziness, tears and laughter
The festival in San Sebastian is called one of the main cultural events in Spain and one of the most important European film competitions.
The Golden Shell winner, director Isaki Lacuesta, told Euronews about his impressions of the festival:
It was wonderful!
We came here as a team and of course we went through dizzying moments, tears, laughter.
We are happy.
We started preparing this film 14 years ago, it was a very long work, and, most importantly for me, we didn't want to stop.
Now it is time for joy and gratitude.
As Euronews correspondent Carlos Marlasca notes, Isaki Lacuesta's film fit seamlessly into the collection of films that received the Golden Shell, "but the San Sebastián festival was not without unexpected, sometimes shocking, jury decisions, which are sometimes even called the calling card of the competition".
