On September 30, 1928, that is, exactly 90 years ago, British bacteriologist Alexander Fleming announced an unprecedented discovery.
The discovery of penicillin marked the beginning of the era of modern antibiotics, brought Fleming worldwide fame, and made him a Nobel laureate.
By the way, the release of penicillin from mold fungi was not Fleming's first discovery.
A few years earlier, when he had a cold, he sowed mucus from his own nose on a petri dish (the kind of glass lid in which bacteria are tested) and a few days later found that the bacteria there had been destroyed.
Almost by accident, he discovered penicillin as well.
Fleming's name was added to a list of the 100 most distinguished individuals in human history.
His discovery, according to many scientists, changed the course of history.
With the help of penicillin, medicine began to cope with most of the most ancient diseases, previously considered incurable - tuberculosis, syphilis, gangrene...
When, shortly after winning the Nobel Prize, Fleming arrived in the French capital in 1945, Paris newspapers wrote: "He did more than dozens of divisions to defeat fascism and liberate France".
Experts estimate that Fleming's discovery of the world's first antibiotic saved the lives of more than 200 million Earth's inhabitants.
Alexander Fleming died at his home in London in 1955 of a heart attack.
He was cremated and, a week later, his ashes were buried in London's famous St Paul's Cathedral.
Where, by the way, my wife and I drew attention to this by a word-hungry Russian-speaking tour guide.
