AfD becomes second most popular in Germany
The anti-immigrant Alternative for Germany is breaking another popularity record, and Angela Merkel's ratings are falling.
Apparently, Germans have begun to tire seriously of Angela Merkel's immigration policies, which have made the country a coveted target for millions of refugees from the Middle East.
Nowhere is this more evident than in recent opinion polls, according to which the anti-immigrant Alternative für Deutschland (AfD) party is becoming increasingly popular and the positions of Merkel and Seehofer's ruling bloc are weakening.
This week, the AfD broke another record, rising to second place in the popular sympathy rankings.
The right-wing conservatives, with 17 percent popularity, have managed to beat the Social Democrats, who have about 16 percent.
The one-percentage-point gap can be attributed to statistical error, but the fact that the AfD, created in 2013 from a small group of Euroskeptic economists, has managed to become a serious political force cannot be ignored.
The overall lead is still held by the ruling CSU / CDU bloc, which has about 30 percent.
But there is a tendency to lose points here - back in April, support for Angela Merkel's bloc was four percentage points higher.
The personal rating of the German chancellor, who heads Germany's government for a fourth consecutive term, is also declining.
Today, 48 percent of Germans back Angela Merkel, down 7 percentage points from last year.
Add that the Social Democrats were followed by the Greens (15%), the Left (11%), and the Liberals (10%).
The evolution of the "Alternative"
The Alternative für Deutschland party was founded in September 2012 on the basis of the Alternative Choice 2013 group, which includes people from the Christian Democratic Union.
The group initially opposed the government's course, but initially focused only on economic issues, including the euro and interaction within the EU.
At the same time, the group opposed Germany's "sponsorship" of weak EU economies, did not rule out the possibility of a return to the deutsche mark and a full exit from the European Union.
With the immigration crisis deepening, the AfD's political platform has broadened.
In 2013, the group emerged as a full-fledged party that took on a Euroskeptic niche and began harshly criticizing the government for its failed immigration policy.
In the last parliamentary election in 2017, the AfD managed to make its way into the Bundestag for the first time, gaining 94 seats (out of 709).
Two representatives of the Alternative for Germany will win seats in the European Parliament.
