Term of Death of the Universe Named
The universe will survive for another 140 billion years or so, which is ten times the age of the observed world of about 13.8 billion years.
The research of an international team of scientists has been posted in the library of electronic preprints arXiv.org and is aimed at publication in the journal Publications of the Astronomical Society of Japan, reports the Japanese newspaper Asahi Shimbun.
Experts reached similar conclusions by observing about ten million galaxies with the Subaru telescope's HSC (Hyper Suprime-Cam).
By tracking the distribution of dark matter and dark energy, which account for more than 95 percent of the energy-mass of the observed world, the scientists, working within the standard cosmological model known as Cold Dark Matter, estimated the rate of expansion of the universe, which was slightly slower than previously thought.
The Subaru Observatory said in a press release that the observations provided a detailed three-dimensional map of the distribution of matter in the universe, and data from the European Planck space telescope clarified the limitations imposed on the CDM parameters.
In July, scientists simulated the possible demise of the universe.
