To press and to dominate - how is it right?
The word pressure does not exist.
The right thing to do is dominate.
The word "pressure" in the sense of "pull, influence, influence" exists only phonetically, because we hear the sound [a] instead of [o] in "dominate".
We use this word in the belief that it comes from the word "pressure".
But "pressure" and "domination" are etymologically not only not close, but even in a sense opposite.
See it for yourself.
To be attracted (church-bookish, obsolete) means "enough, enough, enough, enough for someone or something, enough to satisfy".
To be satisfied, pleasure is kindred words.
Before, it still had the meaning of "not to depend on anything, to be self-sufficient" - "to dominate yourself".
Old Slavonic "dovleti" is related to the words "to command" and "will".
To press, to suppress - completely different.
These words have truly frightening "relatives": daos - "wolf" (pressing sheep), deyja - "to die" and dvaidī - "to oppress".
The similar phonetic appearance of the words "pressure" and "dominate", as well as the inevitable obsolescence of the latter, caused them to enter into contagion.
So we have this very "d", which is also used in writing through "a", which, in a good way, is wrong and impossible from the point of view of the processes of emergence and development of these words.
So, the right thing to do is to dominate.
But the word is obsolete, in its correct meaning no longer used.
If you want to point out that any circumstances / people have a negative influence on you from above, use the word "pressure".
You can also use the "apply pressure" construction, but remember that this is a chancery.
