The main Macedonian opposition leader refused to vote in referendum
Macedonia is holding a referendum on Sunday, September 30, on the issue of an intergovernmental treaty with Greece to rename the Republic of Macedonia.
Citizens are asked to answer one question: "Do you support EU and NATO membership by accepting the agreement between the Republic of Macedonia and the Republic of Greece?"
Nevertheless, the leader of the leading opposition party, the Inner Macedonian Revolutionary Organization - Democratic Party for Macedonian National Unity (VMRO-DPMNE), Christian Mitskoski, has stated that he will not vote in the referendum.
As party spokesman Naum Stoilkowski explained, Mitskoski decided to abstain from the vote in order to express his opposition to the treaty, which he considers "harmful".
According to the spokesman, the current referendum resolves the question of renaming the country and nothing more, whereas the strategic goal of the party is to achieve membership in NATO and the EU.
A week ago, Macedonian President Gjorge Ivanov also refused to participate in the referendum on September 30.
He explained that he chose the name for the country 27 years ago in a referendum on independence. The Macedonian leader considers the renaming of the country a negative factor.
"A new semi-sovereign state with a new name is being created", Ivanov noted.
The agreement on the new official name of the former Yugoslav Republic - the Republic of North Macedonia - was signed by the Foreign Ministers of Macedonia and Greece on June 17 this year during a solemn ceremony on the shore of Lake Prespa, on which the border between the two countries runs.
This treaty should resolve the long-standing dispute over the name of the country, as well as Skopje's path to NATO and the EU, TASS reminds.
